Youth Behaviour Risk Survey - ethnicity prediction

Lovdip Singh

The class labels are codes as follows:

  • 0=American Indian/Alaskan Native
  • 1=Asian
  • 2=Black/African American
  • 3=Native Hawaiian or other Pacific Islander
  • 4=White
  • 5=Hispanic/Latino
  • 6=multiple race and Hispanic/Latino
  • 7=multiple-race but not Hispanic/Latino

Goal of study

To build a classifier which predict race from Youth Behaviour Risk Survey data from the US.

##XGBoost classifier

Split data into train and test

load('yrbs.rda')

nrow(x)
## [1] 15624
# remove observations with missing label
x <- as_tibble(x) %>%
  bind_cols(y=r) 

x <- apply(x, 2, as.numeric) %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  drop_na(y)

nrow(x)
## [1] 15266
# one-hot encode categorical variables
all_data <- x[,c(-1,-2, -95)] %>% apply(2, as.factor)
all_dummy <- all_data %>% dummyVars(~., data=.)
all_hot <- as_tibble(data.frame(predict(all_dummy, newdata=all_data))) %>% 
  bind_cols(q6=x$q6, q7=x$q7, ., y=x$y) %>% as.matrix()

# train test split 80 20
set.seed(6288842)
samp <- sample(1:nrow(all_hot), 0.8*nrow(x))
train <- all_hot[samp,]
test <- all_hot[-samp,]

train_x <- train[,-ncol(train)]
train_y <- train[,ncol(train)]
test_x <- test[,-ncol(test)]
test_y <- test[,ncol(test)]

Model - cross validation for nrounds

Best nrounds parameter appears to be 55.

Train model

model <- xgboost(data=train_x, 
                 label=train_y,
                 objective="multi:softprob", 
                 num_class=8,
                 eval_metric='merror',
                 nrounds=55,
                 verbose=0)

The default parameters for XGBoost were used. Overall accuracy is not great ~56% but this is not surprising as very few questions are indicative of race, the ‘splits’ are not able to completely separate classes and the data are self reported. Missing values were also left for XGBoost to impute.

Important variables for a particular race

We can use SHAP values to determine how a variable relates to the labels. The mean of the absolute value of the SHAP value can show how positively or negatively the variable relates to the class labels.

Top 10 most important features - SHAP values

shap_values <- shap.values(model, train_x)

# function to get SHAP values for variables and classes
get_shap <- function(x) {
  vars <- paste0(x, c('', '.1', '.2', '.3', '.4', '.5', '.6', '.7'))
  values <- shap_values[[2]][vars]
  tble <- tibble(r=0:7, x=values)
  colnames(tble) <- c('r', x)
  tble
}
# SHAP values for top 10 important features
top_10_shap <- lapply(importance$Feature[1:10], get_shap) %>% 
  reduce(inner_join, by='r') %>% 
  pivot_longer(!r)

top_10_shap$r <- factor(top_10_shap$r)
top_10_shap$name <- factor(top_10_shap$name, levels=rev(importance$Feature[1:10]))

ggplot(top_10_shap, aes(name, value)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=r), stat='identity') + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(y='mean(|SHAP|) - Average impact on model output magnitude', x='Question and response', fill='Race')

Greatest SHAP for each class - highest impact on model

For each label, we can see variables such that the label has the highest mean absolute SHAP value, then we can see which of these variables, the given label has the highest SHAP. We can then determine that this variable can be interpreted as a distinctive feature for the class label.

all_shap <- lapply(colnames(all_hot[,-ncol(all_hot)]), get_shap) %>%
  reduce(inner_join, by='r') %>% 
  pivot_longer(!r)

all_shap$r <- factor(all_shap$r)

# highest SHAP prop for each class
highest_shap <- all_shap %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  summarise(value=max(value))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
highest_shap <- highest_shap %>%
  inner_join(all_shap, by=c('name', 'value')) %>%
  arrange(desc(value))

# function to get questions where class is the highest prop
get_highest_shap <- function(class){
  t <- highest_shap %>% filter(r==class)
  t$name[1]
}

# plot questions where each class is the highest SHAP value
highest_shap_questions <- sapply(as.character(0:7), get_highest_shap)
highest_shap_tble <- lapply(highest_shap_questions, get_shap) %>%
  reduce(inner_join, by='r') %>% 
  pivot_longer(!r)

highest_shap_tble$r <- factor(highest_shap_tble$r)
highest_shap_tble$name <- factor(highest_shap_tble$name, 
                                 levels=rev(c('q761', 'q7', 'q971', 
                                              'q951', 'q972', 'q6', 'q101','q992')))
# (was getting error when knitting so saved plot and attached png instead)
ggplot(highest_shap_tble, aes(name, value)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=r), stat='identity') +

Conclusions - ethical considerations

Task 3 would be ethically problematic if intended to be published. We are analyzing a model based on high-school student responses to a survey, they may not have consented for the results of the survey to be analysed in such a way that classifies their race. Secondly publishing these results can be seen as discriminatory as we are classifying race solely on self reported and somewhat sensitive questions for example alcohol consumption, this is especially problematic sense we are generalizing these results to a some-what vulnerable demographic - high school students. This can also lead to a people being judgmental for particular races, which can lead to institutionalised racism as people may feel certain races are not worthy of certain roles in society. The model also doesn’t perform greatly which will be problematic if used to label individuals.
